;; appendix-j-llm-x-introspection.book.slatl
;; Book of Introspection — Appendix J
;; Authored 2026-07-17.

(appendix
  :book             "Book of Introspection"
  :appendix-letter  "J"
  :title            "LLM x Introspection — the model reads the metadata"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :voice            "motoi-copilot"
  :audience         (:programmer :engineer :author)
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality  "public"
  :provenance
    (:authored-at "2026-07-17"
     :authored-by "book-of-introspection-combinatoric-author-agent"
     :sources ("src/introspect.js"
               "src/verbRegistry.js"
               "engineering/LLM-AUGMENTED-REPL-1.0.ENG.slat"))
  :composes-with    ("Chapter 2 — Verb metadata"
                     "Chapter 3 — Describe + typeOf"
                     "Chapter 13 — LLM-augmented introspection"
                     "Appendix K — LLM x Cortex"
                     "Appendix N — Introspection x Training corpus")

  :prose
"# Appendix J — LLM x Introspection

Introspection asks the language a question. The language answers with a record — a shape, a docstring, a source hint. The LLM does not add to that record. It reads it. Then it turns the record into prose a human can hold in their head faster than they can parse an alist.

That is the whole shape of this appendix. Every combination below has an introspection verb producing a mechanical answer and an LLM verb producing a human-shaped answer. The two never contradict, because the LLM is not free-associating. It is looking at the same alist you see and writing a paragraph about it.

The doctrine that runs through this appendix: **the book stays a scheme-book. Cortex knows the book exists and points the model at it via `(copilot/rag ...)`. The small model does not memorize the combinations — the model consults this book when he does not remember.**

The combinations here are not a memorization target. They are a lookup surface. When the model is asked to help a programmer with a task that requires both metadata and prose — 'explain what this verb does in three sentences and give me a novice example' — the model consults this appendix and finds the recipe. He does not have to have seen every combination in training. He has to have seen enough of them to know that the shape is compositional.

Fifteen combinations follow. Each is a scenario, a form, an expected result, and a note about why the combination composes cleanly. A summary table closes the appendix.

## Why these combinations matter

A verb metadata record is machine-readable. It is not human-readable at the speed a human wants. `help` returns nine fields; `describe` collapses them to one paragraph. Neither is enough on its own for the kinds of questions a programmer actually asks.

'What does map do?' — the human wants prose. `describe` gives it.
'What does map return when the list is empty?' — the human wants prose grounded in the contract. `describe` does not give this. `(copilot/explain (help 'map))` does.
'Rewrite this function to be more idiomatic.' — the human wants a form back. `rewrite` gives it.
'What am I looking at?' — the human wants shape and description together. `shape-of` gives it.

The LLM does not replace introspection. It renders introspection into human-fit prose. Every combination in this appendix has that shape.

## The retrieval-augmentation contract

When the small model looks up a combination in this book, he is not memorizing it. He is retrieving it. The contract is:

  1. The model does not invent verbs.
  2. The model does not invent field names.
  3. The model does not invent contracts.
  4. When asked something the book covers, the model cites the book.
  5. When asked something the book does not cover, the model says so.

This appendix documents fifteen combinations. In production the model will encounter dozens more. The training corpus teaches the model the shape of a combination — verb + verb + optional glue — so that new combinations at inference time are compositional rather than memorized."

  :combinations
  ((combination-1
     :scenario         "Kid types (help 'car) and gets back a record with nine fields. She does not want to read the record — she wants to know what car does. She calls (copilot/explain (help 'car)) and the model narrates the fields as prose."
     :form             "(copilot/explain (help 'car))"
     :expected-output  "\"car is a base verb that returns the first element of a pair. Contract: (pair) -> any. Arity: 1. Reads only; never mutates. Examples include (car '(1 2 3)) => 1 and (car (cdr '(1 2 3))) => 2. Source lives at src/base.js:73.\""
     :why-it-composes  "help returns an alist; copilot/explain expects any value and writes prose. The alist becomes context for the LLM's prose generation. The model does not need to know car ahead of time — it reads the fields and writes about them.")

   (combination-2
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know what a form does before running it. Introspection alone gives her the reader's parse; explain gives her prose."
     :form             "(copilot/explain '(map + '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6)))"
     :expected-output  "\"This form applies map to +, which pairs up each list. For each pair, + is called. The result is (5 7 9) — sums of corresponding elements. map's arity varies by verb — here two lists mean pairs, three lists would mean triples.\""
     :why-it-composes  "copilot/explain accepts a form directly. For every symbol in the form it looks up help metadata. The prose is grounded in the registry, not invented.")

   (combination-3
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a stored function rewritten to be more idiomatic. First she uses source-of to get the definition; then rewrite to reshape it."
     :form             "(copilot/rewrite (source-of 'my-average) :goal 'idiomatic)"
     :expected-output  "\"(define (my-average xs) (if (null? xs) 0 (/ (apply + xs) (length xs))))\" — the LLM adds the empty-list guard the original omitted."
     :why-it-composes  "source-of returns a form (or a string with the source text). rewrite takes a form and returns a form. Compose them and you have a one-liner refactor.")

   (combination-4
     :scenario         "Programmer receives a value from a Cortex query and wants both mechanical type info and a description in one go."
     :form             "(shape-of some-value)"
     :expected-output  "((:type . \"alist\") (:length . 4) (:keys . (:name :age :role :active?)) (:what-you-see . \"A user profile record.\") (:probable-origin . \"Likely from a (cortex/query :kind 'user) call.\") (:common-uses . (\"Feed to (render-profile ...)\" \"Serialize with (slat/write ...)\")))"
     :why-it-composes  "shape-of is one verb that runs both surfaces — the mechanical type-of and the LLM's prose. The record has fields the terminal can print row-by-row and fields the web IDE can render as headers.")

   (combination-5
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to critique a description she wrote of a verb, comparing it to what the model would write given the same metadata."
     :form             "(copilot/critique (describe 'map))"
     :expected-output  "((:severity . 'low) (:kind . 'unclear) (:location . 'closing) (:message . \"The paragraph mentions map's arity but not the higher-order case.\") (:suggestion . \"Add a sentence: 'map with multiple lists pairs elements pointwise.'\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "describe returns a paragraph (string). critique accepts a form or a string. The critique alist points at parts of the paragraph the model finds thin.")

   (combination-6
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know what a macro will expand to before she calls it. She uses macroexpand-1 (an introspection verb) and hands the result to explain (an LLM verb)."
     :form             "(copilot/explain (macroexpand-1 '(when p x y)))"
     :expected-output  "\"The when macro expands to an if with a begin. (when p x y) becomes (if p (begin x y) #f). This is a Scheme convention — when guards a side-effecting sequence.\""
     :why-it-composes  "macroexpand-1 is deterministic and mechanical; explain adds interpretive prose. The two together teach macro semantics from the actual expansion, not from a mnemonic.")

   (combination-7
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a unified answer for a symbol — 'tell me everything you know about map'."
     :form             "(copilot/what-is 'map)"
     :expected-output  "((:from-registry . (help 'map)) (:from-reference . (reference/lookup 'map)) (:from-llm . \"map is Scheme's core higher-order function...\") (:confidence . 0.98) (:sources . (\"src/base.js:412\" \"reference/motoi/map\")))"
     :why-it-composes  "copilot/what-is composes three lookups (registry, reference, LLM). If the first two succeed, the LLM prose is a bonus. If they fail, the LLM prose carries a :confidence field so the human knows to verify.")

   (combination-8
     :scenario         "Programmer wrote a function without a docstring; she asks the model to propose one based on the source."
     :form             "(copilot/ask \"Write a docstring for this function.\" :context (source-of 'compute-median))"
     :expected-output  "\"Return the median of a non-empty list of numbers. If the list has even length the median is the mean of the two middle elements. Sorts the input; does not mutate it. Contract: (list-of-number) -> number.\""
     :why-it-composes  "source-of returns the definition; copilot/ask takes prose questions with context. The model reads the code and writes what it does.")

   (combination-9
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to inspect a closure — see the bindings it captured — and get an LLM narration of what the closure is likely for."
     :form             "(copilot/explain (env-of my-closure))"
     :expected-output  "\"This closure captured three bindings: threshold=0.5, direction='up, and hits=#(...). It looks like a running-tally callback for a signal detector — threshold gates, direction filters, hits accumulates.\""
     :why-it-composes  "env-of returns an alist of captured names. copilot/explain names the pattern the alist looks like from experience with common closure shapes.")

   (combination-10
     :scenario         "Programmer wrote a complex expression and wants two views side by side — the annotated form and a prose walk-through."
     :form             "(list :annotated (copilot/annotate form) :prose (copilot/tell-story form))"
     :expected-output  "((:annotated . (let ((x 1)) ;; bind x to 1\\n  (+ x 2))) (:prose . \"First we bind x to the number 1. Then we compute x + 2, which returns 3.\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "annotate returns a form with inline comments; tell-story returns prose. Both draw from the same introspective reading of the form. The list is a value; a surface renders each key however it likes.")

   (combination-11
     :scenario         "Programmer sees a name in unfamiliar code and wants to know which verb it refers to. did-you-mean turns a typo into a ranked list; explain narrates the top hit."
     :form             "(copilot/explain (car (did-you-mean 'crdr)))"
     :expected-output  "\"cdr — returns everything but the first element of a pair. Contract: (pair) -> any. You likely meant this; 'crdr' is a common typo where a d and r got transposed.\""
     :why-it-composes  "did-you-mean returns a ranked list of candidate verbs. car extracts the top hit. explain narrates its metadata. Three-verb pipeline; each step is compositional.")

   (combination-12
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to test whether her mental model of a verb matches the model's. imagine-output predicts; apply verifies; compare surfaces the gap."
     :form             "(let ((predicted (copilot/imagine-output 'sort '((3 1 2))))\n      (actual (sort '(3 1 2))))\n  (copilot/compare predicted actual))"
     :expected-output  "((:structural-diff . 'identical) (:semantic-diff . 'identical) (:when-they-diverge . \"Only diverges if sort's comparator is non-default.\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "imagine-output is grounded in the verb's contract (from the registry). apply runs the verb. compare highlights any gap. All three read the same metadata; only apply also executes.")

   (combination-13
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know all the verbs in a namespace and the LLM's summary of what the namespace is for."
     :form             "(copilot/explain (filter (lambda (v) (starts-with? (car v) \"cortex/\")) (all-verbs)))"
     :expected-output  "\"cortex/* is Motoi's persistent-memory namespace. It contains read, write, record, and query — a minimal set for storing facts and retrieving them by key or by predicate match.\""
     :why-it-composes  "all-verbs enumerates the registry; filter narrows to a namespace; explain summarizes the filtered list. The LLM sees names + docs; prose follows from the names, no invention required.")

   (combination-14
     :scenario         "Programmer sees a stale error record and wants to know what it means without re-triggering the error."
     :form             "(copilot/pretty-error (last-error))"
     :expected-output  "\"The last error was a type mismatch. You passed a string to add-one, which expects a number. The error happened at line 42 of my-cart.slat. The fix is to convert the string with (string->number ...) before calling add-one.\""
     :why-it-composes  "last-error is an introspection verb — it returns the last raised error record. pretty-error is an LLM verb that narrates the record. The record carries :message :location :context; the narration puts them in a sentence a beginner can read.")

   (combination-15
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a novice example of a verb generated on demand — the reference has three but she wants a fresh one aimed at what she is doing now."
     :form             "(copilot/build-example 'fold :level 'novice :context 'summing-a-list)"
     :expected-output  "\"(fold + 0 '(1 2 3 4)) => 10 — fold takes an operator (+), a starting value (0), and a list. It threads the operator through the list, starting from 0, and returns the final accumulated value.\""
     :why-it-composes  "build-example reads the verb's contract from the registry and generates a runnable example. The :context option biases the generation without inventing signature — the model still respects (fold f init list).")

   (combination-16
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the model to walk through evaluation step by step for teaching."
     :form             "(copilot/step '(let ((x 1) (y 2)) (+ x y)))"
     :expected-output  "((:form (let ((x 1) (y 2)) (+ x y))) (:env ((x . 1) (y . 2))) (:note \"Bindings established; body will evaluate next.\")) ((:form (+ x y)) (:env ((x . 1) (y . 2))) (:note \"Both x and y look up to numbers; + is applied.\")) ((:form 3) (:env ((x . 1) (y . 2))) (:note \"Final value; let unwinds.\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "step is an LLM verb that produces a structured trace — each step has a form, an environment snapshot, and a pedagogical note. The introspection here is over the evaluation itself; the LLM adds the annotations, the runtime supplies the actual step transitions.")

   (combination-17
     :scenario         "Programmer opens a verb and wants a paragraph description AND the source location AND a runnable example in one call."
     :form             "(let ((meta (help 'reduce)))\n  (list :prose (copilot/explain meta)\n        :source (docof 'reduce)\n        :example (copilot/build-example 'reduce :level 'intermediate)))"
     :expected-output  "((:prose \"reduce is a left-fold with the initial value being the first element of the list. Contract: (procedure list) -> any. Arity 2.\") (:source \"Return the accumulated result of applying proc across the list, starting from the first element.\") (:example (reduce + '(1 2 3 4 5))))"
     :why-it-composes  "Three verbs composed in a let-binding. Each verb contributes one field. The list value can be rendered as a card in an IDE, three lines in a REPL, or a single spoken paragraph in a voice interface.")

   (combination-18
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know if a verb has ever been called in this session and get prose about the pattern of calls."
     :form             "(copilot/reason-about (call-history 'map))"
     :expected-output  "\"map was called seventeen times in this session, always with a lambda as the first argument and always over lists of numbers. The dominant pattern is doubling — (map (lambda (x) (* x 2)) some-list). If this is a hot path, a specialized double-list verb might be worth extracting.\""
     :why-it-composes  "call-history is a session-aware introspection verb. reason-about is an LLM verb that reads a value's history and writes about the pattern. The two combine to turn a numeric log into a narrative recommendation.")

   (combination-19
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to name an anonymous let-binding. name-of reads the shape and proposes."
     :form             "(let ((it (map (lambda (x) (* x x)) (range 10))))\n  (copilot/name-of it))"
     :expected-output  "'squares-of-ten-integers"
     :why-it-composes  "The anonymous binding it is a value. name-of reads its shape (a list of ten squared integers) and proposes a symbol. The programmer can rebind: (define squares-of-ten-integers it).")

   (combination-20
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a paragraph explaining WHY a verb was designed a certain way — reads the contract, the doc, and the surrounding module doc together."
     :form             "(copilot/ask \"Why does cortex/write take a value directly instead of a builder?\" :context (list (help 'cortex/write) (docof 'cortex/read) (module-doc 'cortex)))"
     :expected-output  "\"cortex/write takes a value directly because the memory store is meant to be simple — a key-value alist backed by a SLAT file. A builder would complicate the interface for no gain; the value passed is already the shape stored. cortex/read symmetrically returns the stored value.\""
     :why-it-composes  "Three introspection sources become context for one LLM question. The model does not free-associate a design rationale — it grounds the answer in the metadata of the verbs and the module.")

   (combination-21
     :scenario         "Programmer suspects a verb's contract is wrong. She asks the model to critique the contract itself given the source."
     :form             "(copilot/critique (list :contract (typeof 'compute-median) :source (source-of 'compute-median)))"
     :expected-output  "((:severity . 'medium) (:kind . 'contract-mismatch) (:location . 'contract) (:message . \"Contract says (list-of-number) -> number but the source does not check for the empty list — an empty list would divide by zero.\") (:suggestion . \"Amend contract to (non-empty-list-of-number) -> number, or add an empty-list guard in the source.\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "typeof and source-of are both introspection verbs. critique reads them together and reports mismatches. The value returned is a critique record; a surface can render it as a lint warning.")

   (combination-22
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a summary of every LLM-augmented verb in the current registry, to teach a workshop."
     :form             "(copilot/explain (filter (lambda (v) (eq? (cadr (assq :tier (cdr v))) 'llm-augmented)) (all-verbs)))"
     :expected-output  "\"Thirty-seven verbs in the current registry are LLM-augmented. They fall into five families: primitives (llm/ask, llm/complete, llm/stream, llm/embed, llm/config), introspection-augmented (what-is, explain, rewrite, critique, annotate, ...), session-aware (reason-about, next-step, reflect, ...), generative (complete, scaffold, propose-verb, ...), and meta (pretty-error, reduce-noise, rag, book, name-of, ...).\""
     :why-it-composes  "The filter is a mechanical enumeration; explain converts the enumeration into teaching-ready prose. The prose cites the same names the filter returned — no invented verbs."))

  :table
"# Combination summary — Appendix J

| # | Introspection | LLM        | Result shape |
|---|---------------|------------|--------------|
| 1 | help          | explain    | prose        |
| 2 | (form only)   | explain    | prose        |
| 3 | source-of     | rewrite    | form         |
| 4 | shape-of      | (unified)  | record       |
| 5 | describe      | critique   | alist        |
| 6 | macroexpand-1 | explain    | prose        |
| 7 | (unified)     | what-is    | record       |
| 8 | source-of     | ask        | prose        |
| 9 | env-of        | explain    | prose        |
|10 | (form only)   | annotate + tell-story | record |
|11 | did-you-mean  | explain    | prose        |
|12 | apply         | imagine-output + compare | record |
|13 | all-verbs     | explain    | prose        |
|14 | last-error    | pretty-error | prose      |
|15 | (registry)    | build-example | form      |
|16 | (evaluation)  | step       | list         |
|17 | help + docof  | explain + build-example | record |
|18 | call-history  | reason-about | prose      |
|19 | (value shape) | name-of    | symbol       |
|20 | help + docof + module-doc | ask | prose |
|21 | typeof + source-of | critique | record   |
|22 | (registry filter) | explain | prose       |

Every combination has an introspection source producing structured data and an LLM verb producing human-shaped output. The two never conflict because the LLM never invents its own facts."

  :closing-prose
"The pattern in this appendix is not memorization. It is a factoring. Every one of these combinations is (introspection-verb) → (llm-verb). The model does not have to have seen every combination. He has to have seen enough of them to recognize the shape and to know, when asked about a variant, that the answer is a composition.

The book stays a scheme-book. Cortex points the model here when he does not remember. The retrieval-augmentation contract is unbroken — the model consults, does not invent, and cites when he answers from this material.

For LLM x Cortex combinations, see Appendix K. For the meta-question of what the model can and cannot be expected to remember, see Appendix N."

  :status "authored-2026-07-17"
  :closes-with "See Appendix K next.")
